we have seen this behaviour before, and it's something we work to fix. When the validator has connection issues with the subtensors, it skips blocks, as a result windows.
How do we as miners deal with this?
This means there is a sync issue until next checkpoint
In theory it means the miner must also skip 906
Otherwise... out of sync
Maybe @AdamW has a better perspective for the miner's side?

It is a fault and we will try and improve on this. I think this happens when the validator is uploading a checkpoint and the gather process times out so it does not process any evals. The best thing you can do for now is to resync with the checkpoint
it would be ideal if we knew which windows the validator missed, or if we can get the list of windows that the validator did process since the last checkpoint
this way miner can sync properly at any given time
right now validator does not expose this information in a shared storage
We are working on a new way for the catch up and it will be uploaded to R2 so should be easier. For now it is only possible if you do parsing of the logs

@templar・3 The day has finally come. Tomorrow we are going to do a new run with Chunked Compressed DiLoCo (CCLoco). There are quite a lot of changes to the protocol and new things. Most importantly for miners and validators is that we now will do a run with a local dataset that is ~160B tokens. This will require ~300GB in RAM. Please prepare the new dataset in the pods by following the instructions in this PR: https://github.com/tplr-ai/templar/pull/408. The new dataset require a new environment variable set `DATASET_SHARDS_PATH` which is the path to the folder of the data.

Because of CCLoco we have some significant changes to the protocol as well. We no longer have an external aggregator since we are not using signed gradients anymore. The window size will be significantly larger and the compression is no longer doing the DCT. All the changes are in this PR https://github.com/tplr-ai/templar/pull/405. The PR is quite big but the most important parts are in the [miner](https://github.com/tplr-ai/templar/blob/feat/local-demo/neurons/miner.py), the [compress file](https://github.com/tplr-ai/templar/blob/feat/local-demo/src/tplr/compress.py). You can also take a look at the new [dataset](https://github.com/tplr-ai/templar/blob/feat/local-demo/src/tplr/sharded_dataset.py) logic and the [samplers](https://github.com/tplr-ai/templar/blob/feat/local-demo/src/tplr/sharded_sampler.py).
